\subsection{Nonlinear Writing and Hardware-Aware Training}
\label{subsec:nl-hat-stress}

\textbf{Erratum disclosure.} During final code audit we identified two bugs in the analog STE backward pass (LTP/LTD branch swap and an extraneous $\mathsf{nl}$ multiplier in second-order correction), fixed at commit \texttt{9cdbe77}. Results reported here for $NL=2.0$ are post-fix; pre-fix severe-NL claims ($\\sim$30\% ceiling, bimodal basin, structural limit) are deprecated and should not be cited. See \texttt{BROADCAST\_HALT\_AND\_REPLICATE\_20260424.md} for audit provenance.

Under the \emph{canonical} nonlinearity ($NL=1.0$), proportional-noise HAT recovers Tiny-ViT to 97.37$\\pm$0.05\%, and Ensemble HAT preserves 86.37$\\pm$1.54\% across 10 fresh arrays (bug-immune; verified by symbolic check that $\\mathsf{ratio}^{0} \\equiv 1$ makes branch mapping irrelevant). This confirms that hardware-aware training is effective when write dynamics are moderately nonlinear.

The severe-nonlinearity regime ($NL=2.0$) presents a harder challenge. Post-fix retraining with verified code yields 82.03$\pm$0.94\% for standard HAT and 80.45$\pm$0.58\% for Ensemble HAT (both from scratch on commit \texttt{9cdbe77}, 10 fresh instances $\\times$ 5 MC). Replication with seed~456 confirms the finding: Standard HAT 80.47$\pm$0.09\% (M5), Ensemble HAT 81.18$\pm$1.68\% (M6). These results confirm the previously reported $\\sim$30\\% floor was a software artifact rather than a physical limit. All M-series checkpoints have zero provenance mismatches under the patched \\texttt{eval\\_fresh\\_instances\\_postfix.py}.

