An exploratory single-run training-ablation cadence scan (Supplementary Fig.~\\SuppFigZeroShot) shows epoch-level resampling reaches 88.41\% (50-epoch training ablation), versus 87.18\% (fixed) and 86.16\% (per-batch), confirming that structured epoch-level resampling rather than per-batch perturbation is the load-bearing schedule choice under canonical $NL=1.0$.

Whether proportional-noise scaling (where $\\sigma \\propto |G|$) can further improve severe-NL recovery beyond the uniform-noise baseline is tested by CX-M3 (seed~123) and CX-M4 (seed~456), both trained from scratch at $NL=2.0$ with $\\mathsf{noise\\_mode}=\\mathsf{proportional}$. A prior checkpoint evaluated at $NL=2.0$ after training at $NL=1.0$ produced 90.88$\\pm$0.11\%; this is an eval-only NL swap and is \textbf{not} a legitimate $NL=2.0$ training result. The M3/M4 results show \textbf{80.71$\pm$0.14\%} (seed~123) and \textbf{80.75$\pm$0.43\%} (seed~456), respectively. Proportional-noise scaling does not outperform the uniform-noise baseline under severe nonlinearity, though it exhibits the lowest cross-instance variance of all tested protocols.

The full accuracy matrix is provided in the Supplementary Information. Tiny-ViT demonstrates superior baseline accuracy and significant recovery under HAT, especially on complex tasks, though it remains sensitive to nonlinear write dynamics.
